President Jacob Zuma on Tuesday sent SA&rsquo;s condolences to Russia as well as the family of the Russian ambassador to Turkey, Andrey Karlov&sbquo; following his assassination on Monday evening&sbquo; in Ankara&sbquo; Turkey.In a statement issued by the Department of International Relations and Co-operation&sbquo; Zuma said: "The South African government joins the international community in condemning this brutal attack against a diplomat&sbquo; which is in violation of the 1961 Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations and the 1963 Vienna Convention on Consular Relations.""We also wish those injured in the attack&sbquo; a speedy and full recovery," Zuma said in the statement."Terrorism in any form and from whichever quarter constitutes one of the most serious threats to international peace and security&sbquo; and any acts of terrorism are criminal&sbquo; unjustifiable and cannot be condoned."The President said in the statement that SA reiterated its commitment to international initiatives aimed at fighting the scourge of terrorism and violent extremism.TMG Digital